photo.title: Financial District from Coit Tower, Pioneer Park, Telegraph Hill, San Francisco, Ca. USA

description._content: To British eyes, US urban zoning like this looks bizarre. The foreground comprises residential streets of three-storey houses with the characteristic San Francisco bay windows (themselves reminiscent of British 20th Century suburban architecture), blending into a narrow band of two-storey office buildings. Then, as abruptly as crossing Washington Street, there rises a wall of high-rise towers including the 48-storey Transamerica Pyramid. Designed by William Pereira & Associates and built 1969-72 for the Transamerica Corporation, the distinctive 260m-tall Transamerica Pyramid was once ranked amongst the world's five tallest buildings; it's now 'merely' the tallest in San Francisco, clearly visible from across the region. It was nearly the world's second tallest, at 305 m (1,000 feet), but the City's Planning Commission was concerned about the view from Nob Hill, off the right of the image. Planning concerns also inspired its tapered shape, which reduces the building's apparent shadow and allows more light to penetrate to street level. The 'wings' rising from the 29th floor accommodate unavoidably vertical elements of the building: two elevator shafts on the east, and a stairwell and a smoke tower on the west. To the immediate right of the Pyramid is Montgomery Street, the original heart of the Financial District and "the Wall Street of the West". As recently as 1830 it was the waterfront, at which ships were able to moor; everything to the left is reclaimed land. Needless to say, the buildings of the Financial District were somewhat smaller in the 19th Century; the 'Manhattanization' of San Francisco didn't occur until the 1960s and 70s. photo.title: Telegraph Hill and the Financial District from San Francisco Bay, Ca. USA

description._content:
This view from offshore highlights why the 87m asl hill between Fisherman's Wharf (Pier 39 is at the right of the foreground) and the Financial District (in the background) was first developed in 1850, when a semaphore signalling station was established to report on the arrival of ships.  Within three years it had been replaced by an electric telegraph station, which itself soon fell out of use, though the 'Telegraph Hill' name stuck.  The site was purchased by local businessmen in 1876 specifically to prevent further development; they donated the land to the city on condition that it became a park.  Aside from being an obvious choice for the location of the 64m-tall Lillian Coit Memorial Tower, opened in 1933, Pioneer Park is also known for its resident wild parrots.

Needless to say, the buildings of the Financial District were somewhat smaller in 1850; the 'Manhattanization' of San Francisco didn't occur until the 1960s and 70s.  The skyline features four successively holders of the record for 'tallest building in California' (and hence tallest west of west of the Mississippi) 1964-74: at 142 m, the Hartford Building at 650 California St. was tallest when built in 1964, but surrendered the title to the 172 m 44 Montgomery (once the world headquarters for Wells Fargo Bank) on its completion in 1967.  555 California Street, still the second tallest building in the city and largest by floor area, reached 237 m in 1969, but was overtaken by the dramatic 260 m Transamerica Pyramid in 1972. That in turn is now 'merely' the tallest in the city and in the top 200 worldwide.
The city's third tallest, incidentally, is the twin-towered 345 California Center, 189 m tall to roof level but 220 m if the spires are included.

photo.title: "Enchanted Bay"

description._content:
This reminds me of a Buddha sitting in enlightenment. Which is why I almost named it, "Enlightened Bay", but felt it had a more magical feel to it. Came here to shoot the moon lineup over Coit as i've been wanting to shoot this for a few years, but always got kicked out by cops closing the Van ness pier. Was gonna come here on the full moon, but got the Transamerica lineup instead as it was a more original comp in my mind.
 
Came here at 9pm to get set up for the moon and was prepared to sneak in if possible but, to my surprise, the gate was completely open. I was in awe thinking, "Nah, this can't be possible." The moon was set to rise at 9:23pm, which doesn't mean it's visible by then; just means to get cocked and ready. Was taking some test shots and sure enough a cop comes in on foot with K-9 dog saying, "Were closing up. This usually is closed by sundown." A random photographer and I, which turned out to be Jill Zwicky﻿, kindly asked the officer (of course with a little desperation and conviction in our voices) if we could shoot the moon as we were waiting for it to rise. He said, "Ok. FIne. I'll give you 10 minutes." We kindly said thank you knowing it would take alot more than 10 minutes. In fact, i'd say that 10 minutes turned into around an hour as I shot this at exactly 9:55pm. The moon rose behiind some nice, thin texture giving it a diffused kind of halo around Coit Tower. 

Was a very nice bonus with the laser beams flying all around too, as i've never seen any shots with this in it at this location. Finally after the moon rose past the height of Coit, we decided to head back towards the gate. The cop was actually sitting in his car waiting for us to shoot this for almost an hour. I'd say that's pretty much unheard of. Felt like VIP status!

What a night!

Thanks for looking!

 Comments and sharing of insights are always welcomed!

Technical:
50mm primeF/1.8 @ 0.4sec
ISO 400

p.s Took some bracketed shots for moon with more detail but still learning the blending process and was pretty pleased with this shot :)

photo.title: The Coit Tower, San Francisco, CA

description._content:
Coit Tower, also known as the Lillian Coit Memorial Tower, is a 210-foot tower in the Telegraph Hill neighborhood of San Francisco.  The tower, in the city's Pioneer Park, was built in 1933 using Lillie Hitchcock Coit's bequest to beautify the city of San Francisco; at her death in 1929 Coit left one-third of her estate to the city for civic beautification.  The tower was proposed in 1931 as an appropriate use of Coit's gift.  It was added to the National Register of Historic Places on January 29, 2008.

The art deco tower, built of unpainted reinforced concrete, was designed by architects Arthur Brown, Jr. and Henry Howard, with fresco murals by 27 different on-site artists and their numerous assistants, plus two additional paintings installed after creation off-site.

description._content:
This is a 1.1 gigapixel (15,000h x 75,000w, 1x5 ratio) view of San Francisco reduced to 10% of its original width and height.  It 
was created from 100, 11-20-second exposures with the 21 megapixel Canon 5D MKII, and a Canon 400L 5.6 lens.  The photos 
were taken just after sunset from the Marin Headlands on several different evenings under similar lighting conditions.  

All of this effort was required to produce an image that would appear to be taken during that 10-minute period that happens 
about 20 minutes after sunset when the fading daylight and the city lights reach equilibrium.  This could easily be printed at 34ft 
wide by 6 ft tall (200dpi) with fine resolution with little to no pixelation or noise visible at a viewing distance of 1 foot!

I used AutoPano stitching software at first, however as with the other panorama, it (and other stitchers) became hopelessly 
confused by the numerous bridge cables since one looks like another.  So most of this image was hand stitched by me in 
Photoshop.  Also, I did not use a Gigapan machine or a tripod, I used a plastic bucket, a x-large pizza-sized plywood round and 
some wood shims.  This was far more stable than a tripod in the wind with a huge lens, and easier to level and pan across.

Please contact me, Patrick Smith, at patrick @ patricksmithphotography.com with any questions.  The 2.5 gigabyte 8-bit psb file is 
for sale starting at US $4,995.00 for the 34 foot version with lower prices for smaller files.  There are places that will print files of 
this size!

photo.title: Coit Tower at night, seen from the Aquarium of the Bay, San Francisco, Ca. USA

description._content:
I understand that the Tower isn't routinely illuminated at night (in colour, anyway), though in recent years it has been briefly lit in orange, red or blue to celebrate local sporting victories or commemorate firefighters killed on duty; on this occasion, I presume it was for the America's Cup, based at Piers 27/29 at the foot of Telegraph Hill. 

The elegant 64m-tall Lillian Coit Memorial Tower, a simple white column nesting three unpainted concrete cylinders, was designed by Arthur Brown Jr. (also architect of San Francisco City Hall) and built at the summit of Telegraph Hill, soon becoming one of San Francisco's major landmarks; its public observation platform, 54 m above the hilltop (141 m asl), is a popular tourist attraction.

A somewhat eccentric socialite, Lillie Hitchcock Coit was a life-long supporter of the local volunteer fire companies, becoming an honorary firefighter as mascot of Knickerbocker Engine Co. 5 and actually assisting in call-outs.  At her death in 1929, a third of her estate, $118,000, was left to the city for civic beautification.  This funded a statue commemorating firefighters and, with a further $7,000 from city funds, this Art Deco tower on Telegraph Hill, which was completed and dedicated in October 1933.  Its resemblance to a firehose's nozzle is apparently coincidental.

In 1934, as a 'New Deal' federal programme to give artists gainful employment through the production of public artworks, the interior of the Tower's base was painted with murals by 27 artists, most from the California School of Fine Arts.  Depicting life in California during the Depression, some of the subject matter was controversial and was even painted-over before the opening.

The 87m asl hill between Fisherman's Wharf and the Financial District was first developed in 1850, when a semaphore signalling station was established to report on the arrival of ships.  Within three years it had been replaced by an electric telegraph station, which itself soon fell out of use, though the name stuck.  The site was purchased by local businessmen in 1876 specifically to prevent further development; they donated the land to the city on condition that it became a park.  Aside from being an obvious choice for the location of the commemorative tower, Pioneer Park is also known for its resident wild parrots.

Though Coit Tower is a San Francisco Designated Landmark, on the National Register of Historic Places, technically the site of the telegraph station carries the status of a California Historical Landmark, not the Tower.

The distinctive Transamerica Pyramid, San Francisco's tallest building, peeks over Telegraph Hill from the Financial District, 1.6 km away.

photo.title: City Lights

description._content:
There are few things as impressive as a city skyline just after dusk.  Sparkling lights and the glow from many street lamps and cars are set against an indigo sky.   It sure can make for great images.   San Francisco's skyline is arguably the most stunning of all California cities.   You can't aim your camera without getting a famous landmark in the skyline.   

In this shot the most dominate feature is the Transamerica Pyramid rising 48 floors before it is capped off by an illuminated facade.   

On the lower right you can just catch the twin spires of Nuestra Senora De Guadalupe Church (Our Lady of Guadalupe Church).  The church was build in 1906 and then rebuild in 1912 at the foot of Russian Hill on Broadway and Mason.   The Powell-Mason cable car will take you right to it.   I did as much leaning as possible to try and get these unique structures into the shot. 

Of course, off in the distance is San Francisco's second most famous suspension bridge known simply as the Bay Bridge.   Unlike the Golden Gate Bridge, its mainstay cables are illuminated with a chain of bright lights and can be seen for miles.  

The big dark tower on the right is the Bank of America Center.  A 52 story skyscraper it's San Francisco's second tallest building.   It's been renamed to 555 California Street when BOA moved its headquarters across the country but most people here still know it as the Bank of America Tower.  

To the lower left, the neon glow of San Francisco's red-light district (technically more of a pink-light district) illuminates Broadway street with its many strip clubs, night clubs and bars.  A touch of the Barbary coast remains nestled just off the Embarcadero. 

This is just a small sample of the interesting views San Francisco has to offer at night.

photo.title: North-eastern side of Telegraph Hill, San Francisco, Ca. USA

description._content: Seen from the Alcatraz ferry terminal at Pier 33. The 87m asl hill between Fisherman's Wharf and the Financial District was first developed in 1850, when a semaphore signalling station was established to report on the arrival of ships. Within three years that had been replaced by an electric telegraph station, which itself soon fell out of use, though the name stuck. The site was purchased by local businessmen in 1876 specifically to prevent commercial/residential development; they donated the land to the city on condition that it became a park. In 1882, Frederick O. Layman opened a wooden 'German castle' in Pioneer Park as a cable car terminus, public observatory and restaurant; I'm not sure whether the business venture succeeded, but in 1903 'Layman’s Folly', already disused (I think), burned down, the site becoming an obvious choice for the location of the Coit Tower some years later. Designed in a unique combination of Gothic Revival and Arts and Crafts styles (and presumably inspired by Layman’s Folly) by Luigi Mastropasqua for fellow immigrant Julius Roz, Julius' Castle, in the lower middle of the image, was built in 1923-4, though the hexagonal tower and redwood lettering were added in 1928. Roz died in 1943, but the name of the landmark (literally - it's an official San Francisco Landmark) restaurant was retained by subsequent owners. Though popular as a 'special-occasion' venue (the entire cast of 'The Empire Strikes Back' visited one evening, and a party of elderly mountaineers including Sir Edmund Hillary on another occasion), the restaurant, newly renovated, closed in 2007 and has yet to reopen – though fresh work since this photo was taken means it's more likely. The elegant 64m-tall Lillian Coit Memorial Tower, a simple white column formed of three nested, unpainted concrete cylinders, was designed by Arthur Brown Jr. (also architect of San Francisco City Hall) and built at the summit of the Hill, soon becoming one of San Francisco's major landmarks; its public observation platform, 54 m above the hilltop (141 m asl), is a popular tourist attraction. A somewhat eccentric socialite, Lillie Hitchcock Coit was a life-long supporter of the local volunteer fire companies, becoming an honorary firefighter as mascot of Knickerbocker Engine Co. 5 and actually assisting in call-outs. At her death in 1929, a third of her estate, $118,000, was left to the city for civic beautification. This funded a statue commemorating firefighters and, with a further $7,000 from city funds, this Art Deco tower, which was completed and dedicated in October 1933. Its resemblance to a firehose's nozzle is apparently coincidental. In 1934, as a 'New Deal' federal programme to give artists gainful employment through the production of public artworks, the interior of the Tower's base was painted with murals by 27 artists, most from the California School of Fine Arts. Depicting life in California during the Depression, some of the subject matter was controversial and was even painted-over before the opening.
